  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project will  provide support to approximately 3,360 people with access to seeds and tools in order to 
enable them to grow food and ensure the long term survival of their families. 

This will be achieved through the provision of seeds and livestock to 510 Ebola survivors in rural communities; 
The seeds provided will be rice,  cassava,  potatoes, groundnuts and green vegetables. In 
addition the project will provide male and female goats as well as hens and cockerels, to provide families will 
vital sources of eggs and milk. The beneficiaries will be able to quickly harvest their food by August this year, 
and this will mean that they have a sustainable source of food and income for many months to come, whist 
also meeting their basic needs for food in the coming weeks.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Expected Outcomes Total project of 6 partners
3,060  survivors  and   other   vulnerable   people   severely   affected   by   the      Ebola  virus  will   have  the   ability   to 

support themselves with vital access to food, without which they cannot survive. The project will also have a 
knock on effect on thousands of other people by bringing down the price of food and making it more widely 
available   to   others  in   the  community.  Many   Ebola   survivors   have   been   left   with   nothing,  their  homes   and 
belongings  having been destroyed  in the decontamination process, and therefore this project  will  also  help 
restore their dignity and hope for the future, which is of crucial  importance as the stigma suffered  by Ebola 
survivors remains rife. This project will enable the families to move forward and build a new life, free of Ebola.</narrative>
  </description>
